.TH MINIOS-SESSION-CLI 1 "August 2025" "MiniOS" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
minios-session-cli \- command-line interface for managing MiniOS persistent sessions
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B minios-session-cli
[\fIcommand\fR] [\fIoptions\fR]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B minios-session-cli
is a command-line utility for managing MiniOS persistent sessions from within the running system.
It provides full control over session operations including viewing, creating, activating, and deleting sessions.
.SH COMMANDS
.TP
.B list
List all available sessions with detailed information including ID, mode, version, edition, size, and last modification time.
.TP
.B current
Show information about the currently active session.
.TP
.B activate \fIsession_id\fR
Activate the specified session by setting it as the default session. This change takes effect on the next boot.
.TP
.B create [\-\-mode \fImode\fR] [\-\-size \fIsize\fR]
Create a new session with the specified mode and optional size. The new session will be automatically assigned the next available ID.
.TP
.B delete \fIsession_id\fR
Delete the specified session by ID. Cannot delete the currently active session.
.TP
.B cleanup [\-\-days \fIN\fR]
Delete all sessions older than N days (default: 30). The currently active session is never deleted.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.B \-\-mode \fImode\fR
Used with the create command to specify the session mode. Valid modes are:
.RS
.TP
.B native
Direct storage on POSIX-compatible filesystems (ext4, btrfs, etc.). This is the default and most efficient mode for compatible filesystems.
.TP
.B dynfilefs
Dynamic file-based storage suitable for non-POSIX filesystems (FAT32, NTFS). Creates expandable container files.
.TP
.B raw
Fixed-size image file storage compatible with any filesystem. Requires pre-allocation of storage space.
.RE
.TP
.B \-\-size \fIN\fR
Used with the create command to specify the size in MB for dynfilefs and raw modes. Default is 4000 MB (4GB).
.TP
.B \-\-days \fIN\fR
Used with the cleanup command to specify the age threshold in days for session deletion.
.SH SESSION MODES
MiniOS supports three persistence modes for different storage scenarios:
.TP
.B Native Mode
Stores changes directly on the filesystem using standard directories and files. Requires a POSIX-compatible filesystem that supports symbolic links, file permissions, and other Unix features. This is the most efficient mode and should be used on ext4, btrfs, xfs, and similar filesystems.
.TP
.B DynFileFS Mode
Stores changes in dynamically expandable container files using the DynFileFS FUSE utility. Suitable for filesystems that don't fully support POSIX features like FAT32 and NTFS. The container files grow as needed and automatically split at 4GB boundaries to work around filesystem limitations. Requires the dynfilefs package to be installed.
.TP
.B Raw Mode
Stores changes in fixed-size image files. Compatible with any filesystem but requires pre-allocation of storage space. The image size is set when the session is created and cannot be easily changed later.
.SH FILESYSTEM COMPATIBILITY
The tool automatically detects your media's filesystem type and restricts session creation to compatible modes:
.TP
.B POSIX Filesystems (ext2/3/4, btrfs, xfs, f2fs)
All session modes supported. Native mode recommended for best performance.
.TP
.B FAT32 (vfat, msdos)
Only DynFileFS and Raw modes supported. Raw images limited to 4GB maximum due to filesystem constraints.
.TP
.B NTFS and exFAT
Only DynFileFS and Raw modes supported. No file size limitations.
.TP
.B Read-only Media
No session creation possible. Sessions can only be activated or listed.
.PP
Use the
.B info
command to check filesystem compatibility before creating sessions.
.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
.B minios-session-cli list
List all available sessions with detailed information.
.TP
.B minios-session-cli current
Show information about the currently active session.
.TP
.B minios-session-cli info
Show filesystem type and compatible session modes for the current media.
.TP
.B minios-session-cli create --mode native
Create a new session using native mode (direct filesystem storage).
.TP
.B minios-session-cli create --mode dynfilefs
Create a new session using dynamic file-based storage (4GB default size).
.TP
.B minios-session-cli create --mode dynfilefs --size 8000
Create a new DynFileFS session with 8GB initial size.
.TP
.B minios-session-cli activate 2
Activate session #2 as the default session for next boot.
.TP
.B minios-session-cli delete 3
Delete session #3 (cannot delete currently active session).
.TP
.B minios-session-cli cleanup --days 30
Delete all sessions older than 30 days.
.TP
.B minios-session-cli cleanup --days 7
Delete all sessions older than 7 days.
.SH FILES
.TP
.B /run/initramfs/changes/
Primary location for session data and metadata.
.TP
.B /run/initramfs/changes/session.json
Session metadata in JSON format (preferred).
.TP
.B /run/initramfs/changes/session.conf
Session metadata in legacy format (fallback).
.TP
.B /run/initramfs/changes/[0-9]+/
Individual session directories containing persistent changes.
.TP
.B /etc/minios-release
System version and edition information used for session compatibility checking.
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
.B 0
Success
.TP
.B 1
Error occurred (invalid arguments, session not found, permission denied, etc.)
.SH NOTES
.PP
Session activation only updates metadata and takes effect on the next boot. To switch sessions in the current boot, you would need to restart the system with appropriate boot parameters.
.PP
The tool automatically detects the session storage location and format, trying multiple common paths and both JSON and legacy configuration formats.
.PP
Session compatibility is checked based on MiniOS version and edition. Incompatible sessions can still be activated but may cause system instability.
.PP
The utility automatically requests authentication via PolicyKit (pkexec) when operations require elevated privileges. Read operations typically don't require authentication, while write operations (create, activate, delete) will prompt for user authentication.
.SH PRIVILEGE ESCALATION
Operations are categorized by privilege requirements:
.TP
.B Read Operations (list, current, info)
Usually executed without privilege escalation. May require authentication only if session directories have restricted access.
.TP
.B Write Operations (create, activate, delete)
Automatically use pkexec to request user authentication when needed. Uses PolicyKit policy dev.minios.session-manager.write.
.TP
.B Administrative Operations (cleanup)
May require administrator authentication for system-level cleanup operations. Uses PolicyKit policy dev.minios.session-manager.admin.
